properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:

Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant amounts of snow are expected. Up to 35 cm of snow by Sunday night. A low pressure centre and associated surface trough will approach the northern Alaska Panhandle tonight spreading snow and strong winds to the South Klondike Highway and the Haines Road. Snowfall amounts will range from 25 to 35 cm for the Haines Road and 30 to 40 cm for the South Klondike Highway before the snow eases Sunday night. Blowing snow will also be a concern due to strong south to southwest winds. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and persistent visibility near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard returns for Sunday. The pressure gradient will increase across the Richardson Mountains once again as the Beaufort ridge of high pressure rebuilds and a low centre approaches the southern Yukon on Sunday. Winds will increase to 80 km/h with gusts to 100 over the Richardson Mountains early on Sunday morning. These winds will generate blowing snow with near zero visibility near the Richardson Mountains. Blizzard conditions are expected to end late Sunday night as the winds diminish. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Road closures are likely. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Wreckhouse Wind Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds are expected or occurring. Maximum gusts: southeasterly up to 100 km/h in the Wreckhouse area. Time span: midnight Sunday night to Monday morning. Remarks: Strong southeasterly winds will develop overnight Sunday night. Winds will ease upon shifting to southwesterly Monday morning. ### Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Wreckhouse wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and strong winds are expected over the North Shore. A low pressure system moving up the Eastern Seaboard will bring snow over the North Shore from Sunday evening until Tuesday morning. The snow combined with strong winds could reduce significantly the visibilities in blowing snow. Travel conditions are expected to be dangerous due to reduced visibilities. Stay tuned for future forecasts for more information. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
